---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import services from '../../data/services.json';

export function getStaticPaths() {
  return services.map(service => ({
    params: { slug: service.slug },
    props: { service },
  }));
}

const { service } = Astro.props;

const related = services
  .filter(s => s.slug !== service.slug)
  .slice(0, 3);

/* ───────────────────────────────────────────────
   Unique content map — every slug gets its own
   meta description, body paragraphs, and FAQs.
   ─────────────────────────────────────────────── */

const contentMap: Record<string, {
  metaDescription: string;
  paragraphs: string[];
  faqs: { question: string; answer: string }[];
}> = {
  'decorative-concrete-curbing': {
    metaDescription: 'Custom decorative concrete curbing in Utah — 14 colors, 10 stamp patterns, 4 styles. Same-week scheduling by Buzz Co Curbing.',
    paragraphs: [
      `Decorative concrete curbing is the flagship service at Buzz Co — the one that turns a "landscaped" yard into a "designed" one. It's the difference between mulch that drifts onto the sidewalk and a clean, deliberate border that makes every bed, pathway, and tree look intentional. We pour continuous concrete borders directly on-site, custom-shaped to your yard's exact layout with no seams, no joints, and no prefab pieces.`,
      `Where most companies offer a handful of options, we give you the full range: 14 integral concrete colors, 10 stamp patterns (from flagstone to running brick to wood grain), and 4 curb profiles — including our popular mower-friendly style. Every combination is poured to order, which means your curbing matches your home's exterior, your landscape rock, and the look you actually want — not the three options some guy has on his truck.`,
      `Justin still walks every Logan-area job before it starts. He'll come out in the evening when both homeowners can be there, sketch the layout together, show you color and pattern samples in person, and give you a firm price on the spot. If it works, the crew is there the next morning. No three-week wait, no surprise line items. Your yard transforms in about 24 hours.`,
      `Concrete curbing lasts decades when installed correctly. Our borders are poured over a compacted base, reinforced with continuous extrusion, and sealed to protect against UV fading and freeze-thaw cycles. Utah's climate is hard on everything — our curbing is built to handle it. Whether you're defining flower beds, bordering walkways, or framing your entire yard, decorative concrete curbing is the permanent upgrade your landscaping has been missing.`,
    ],
    faqs: [
      {
        question: 'How much does decorative concrete curbing cost?',
        answer: 'Most residential projects fall between $5 and $9 per linear foot, depending on curb style, color, and stamp pattern. A typical front-yard install of 150–250 feet runs between $750 and $2,250. We quote on-site so you get an exact number — no ballpark ranges over the phone.',
      },
      {
        question: 'How long does concrete curbing last?',
        answer: 'Properly installed and sealed concrete curbing lasts 20 years or more. Utah\'s freeze-thaw cycles can be tough on outdoor concrete, which is why we seal every job and recommend re-sealing every 2–3 years to keep the color vibrant and the surface protected.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Can you match my existing concrete or stone colors?',
        answer: 'Yes. We carry 14 integral colors that are mixed into the concrete itself — not painted on top. During your walkthrough, we bring sample chips so you can hold them against your home\'s exterior, landscape rock, or existing hardscape to find the closest match.',
      },
    ],
  },

  'landscape-edging': {
    metaDescription: 'Permanent concrete landscape edging in Utah — replace plastic and metal borders that shift. Same-week scheduling from Buzz Co. Get a free estimate.',
    paragraphs: [
      `If you've spent any time fighting with plastic edging that pops out of the ground or metal strips that rust and bend, you already know the problem. Those products are sold as "easy solutions," but within a season or two they're sticking up at odd angles, letting mulch spill onto the lawn, and making your yard look worse than it did before you installed them. Concrete landscape edging solves this permanently.`,
      `We pour continuous concrete borders directly along your bed lines, creating a solid, ground-level edge that keeps mulch, rock, and soil exactly where they belong. The concrete is extruded on-site using a machine that follows whatever curves and angles your landscape requires — no cutting, no fitting, no gaps. Once it cures, that edge isn't moving. Not this year, not in ten years.`,
      `Our edging profiles range from a low, flat mower strip to a taller raised border, depending on what you're containing and how you want it to look. If your beds are filled with decorative rock, a taller profile keeps everything in place even on slopes. For mulch beds along a lawn, a mower-style profile lets you run your wheel right along the edge and skip the hand trimmer entirely.`,
      `Installation is fast. Most residential edging jobs are quoted in the evening and poured the next morning. We show up, lay out the lines, prep the base, and extrude the concrete in a single pass. By the end of the day, you have clean, permanent borders that redefine your entire landscape. No more re-staking plastic every spring. No more rock migrating into the grass. Just a clean line that holds.`,
    ],
    faqs: [
      {
        question: 'What\'s the difference between landscape edging and curbing?',
        answer: 'The terms overlap quite a bit. "Edging" usually refers to a lower-profile border meant to separate lawn from beds at ground level. "Curbing" can mean a taller, more decorative profile with stamp patterns and color. At Buzz Co, we pour both — just different profiles on the same machine. You pick the height and style that fits your yard.',
      },
      {
        question: 'How deep is the foundation for concrete edging?',
        answer: 'We extrude the concrete into a prepared trench about 3–4 inches deep, which gives the border a solid footing below grade. This below-ground portion is what prevents the edging from shifting or heaving — something plastic and metal products can\'t match because they sit on the surface.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Does concrete edging require maintenance?',
        answer: 'Very little. We seal the concrete after installation to protect the color and surface. After that, we recommend re-sealing every 2–3 years and clearing soil or debris that builds up against the edge. That\'s it. No re-staking, no bending it back into shape, no annual replacement.',
      },
    ],
  },

  'flower-bed-borders': {
    metaDescription: 'Concrete flower bed borders in Utah — flowing curves, sharp angles, any shape your garden needs. Same-week scheduling from Buzz Co Curbing.',
    paragraphs: [
      `Flower beds deserve borders that match the care you put into planting them. A well-designed garden with loose mulch spilling onto the walkway or lawn looks unfinished — no matter how good the plants are. Concrete flower bed borders give your garden a defined frame that holds everything in place and turns individual beds into a cohesive landscape design.`,
      `What makes concrete borders ideal for flower beds is the design flexibility. Our extrusion machine follows whatever path you lay out — sweeping curves around a patio, tight angles along a fence line, kidney shapes around a water feature, or long flowing borders that connect multiple beds. There's no minimum radius on curves and no maximum on straight runs. If you can draw it, we can pour it.`,
      `We install borders in 14 integral colors and 10 stamp patterns, so the finished product complements your garden aesthetic. A natural flagstone pattern in a warm sandstone color looks completely different from a smooth profile in charcoal — both are concrete, but they fit entirely different yards. During your walkthrough, we bring samples so you can see the options against your actual plants, soil, and hardscape.`,
      `Most homeowners worry about plant roots, and it's a fair question. Our borders are poured along the surface and only extend 3–4 inches below grade. They define the bed boundary without cutting into the root zone of established plants. For new beds, borders are best installed before planting so the layout is locked in. For existing beds, we work around what's already growing. Your flowers stay put — and now they have a border that stays put too.`,
    ],
    faqs: [
      {
        question: 'Can you pour curved shapes for flower bed borders?',
        answer: 'Absolutely. Our machine is designed for curves — that\'s actually where concrete curbing shines compared to straight-line materials like brick or pavers. We can follow any organic shape: kidney beds, S-curves around trees, circular island beds, or flowing lines that connect multiple garden areas.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Is there a minimum bed size for concrete borders?',
        answer: 'No hard minimum, but the smallest practical border run is about 10–15 linear feet — enough for a small tree ring or compact flower bed. For very small beds (under 6 feet across), the setup and mobilization cost may make other materials more cost-effective. We\'ll tell you honestly during the estimate.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Will the curbing damage existing plant roots?',
        answer: 'No. Our borders are surface-installed with a shallow 3–4 inch footing. We don\'t dig deep trenches or pour wide foundations. For beds with established plants, we route the border along the existing edge without disturbing root systems. We\'ve bordered hundreds of mature gardens without plant loss.',
      },
    ],
  },

  'tree-rings': {
    metaDescription: 'Concrete tree rings in Utah — protect roots, contain mulch, add clean detail. Custom sized for any tree. Same-week scheduling from Buzz Co Curbing.',
    paragraphs: [
      `A tree ring does two things at once: it protects the root system from mower damage and string trimmers, and it creates a clean mulch boundary that keeps your landscape looking intentional. Without a ring, mulch drifts, grass creeps in, and the base of the tree becomes the messiest spot in the yard. With a concrete ring, it becomes one of the sharpest.`,
      `We custom-size every tree ring to fit the trunk and canopy. Young trees get smaller rings with room to grow. Mature trees with wide root flares get rings sized to clear the base without sitting on top of roots. There's no standard diameter — we measure on-site and pour to fit. Circles, ovals, and free-form shapes are all on the table, depending on your yard layout and aesthetic.`,
      `Because we extrude the concrete on-site, tree rings are poured as one continuous piece with no seams or joints. This matters for durability — segmented rings shift apart over time as the ground settles, creating gaps where mulch escapes and weeds sneak in. A continuous ring stays locked in position. We install the border at grade level or slightly raised, depending on whether you're containing mulch or creating a visual accent.`,
      `If you have multiple trees, we can pour all of them in a single visit. Most multi-tree jobs are still done in one morning. We match the color and style across all rings so they look like part of a unified landscape plan — not afterthoughts added one at a time. Pair tree rings with matching flower bed borders or walkway edging and the whole yard ties together.`,
    ],
    faqs: [
      {
        question: 'Will concrete tree rings damage tree roots?',
        answer: 'No. Our rings are surface-installed with a shallow 3–4 inch footing — we\'re not digging into the root zone. We also size the ring to clear the root flare, so the concrete doesn\'t press against the trunk or surface roots. Arborists actually recommend defined borders around trees to prevent mower and trimmer damage to bark.',
      },
      {
        question: 'What diameter range can you pour?',
        answer: 'We pour tree rings as small as 3 feet in diameter (for young ornamental trees) up to 10+ feet for large shade trees. The size is based on your tree\'s root flare and canopy, plus how much mulch area you want inside the ring. We measure on-site and recommend a diameter during the walkthrough.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Can you do multiple trees in one visit?',
        answer: 'Yes, and it\'s actually more cost-effective. Setup and mobilization is the same whether we pour one ring or six. We typically handle 3–6 tree rings in a single morning, all in matching colors and styles. If your yard has a row of trees or scattered specimens, we\'ll layout all of them during the evening estimate.',
      },
    ],
  },

  'driveway-borders': {
    metaDescription: 'Concrete driveway borders in Utah — boost curb appeal, prevent gravel spread, define edges. Same-week scheduling from Buzz Co Curbing.',
    paragraphs: [
      `Your driveway is the first thing people see when they pull up to your house. If the edges are ragged — gravel spilling into the lawn, asphalt crumbling at the margins, or no defined line between the drive and the landscape — it drags down the entire front yard. Concrete driveway borders fix this in a single morning.`,
      `We pour continuous concrete borders along one or both sides of your driveway, creating a clean edge that separates the driving surface from the landscaping. For gravel and loose-fill driveways, this means rock stays on the drive instead of migrating into the yard. For asphalt and concrete driveways, the border provides a finished frame that looks intentional — like the driveway was designed, not just poured and forgotten.`,
      `Driveway borders take a beating. Cars clip them, snowplows push against them, and Utah's freeze-thaw cycles test everything outdoors. We pour our borders with a wider base profile specifically for driveway applications, and the continuous extrusion means there are no joints or seams where cracking starts. The result is a border that handles real-world traffic without splitting apart after the first winter.`,
      `Style options are the same as our other curbing — 14 colors, 10 stamp patterns, 4 profiles. Most homeowners match their driveway borders to their flower bed or walkway curbing for a consistent look across the whole property. If you're doing the front yard and want maximum curb appeal, driveway borders paired with bed borders are the highest-impact combination we install. Evening quote, next-morning pour, and your front yard looks completely different by the time your neighbors get home from work.`,
    ],
    faqs: [
      {
        question: 'How close to the driveway surface can you install borders?',
        answer: 'We pour right up against the driveway edge — typically within a half inch of the existing surface. For concrete driveways, the border butts directly against the slab edge. For asphalt, we allow a small gap for thermal expansion. The result is a tight, clean line with no visible gap between the drive and the border.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Do driveway borders affect snow removal?',
        answer: 'Not if you\'re using a standard plow or snowblower. Our borders sit at or just above grade level, so plow blades ride right over them. If you shovel by hand, the border actually helps — it gives you a defined edge to push snow toward. We do recommend a mower-friendly or flat profile along driveways for the smoothest transition.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Do you offer standard and custom widths?',
        answer: 'Our standard driveway border is about 6 inches wide, which works for most residential applications. We can go wider (up to 10–12 inches) if you want a more prominent look or need extra containment for gravel driveways. Width is discussed during the on-site estimate and doesn\'t significantly change the per-foot cost.',
      },
    ],
  },

  'walkway-borders': {
    metaDescription: 'Concrete walkway borders in Utah — create clean, defined pathways through your yard. Same-week scheduling from Buzz Co Curbing.',
    paragraphs: [
      `A walkway without borders is just a path through the grass. Add concrete edges and it becomes a design element — a defined corridor that leads visitors through your landscape with purpose. Whether it's the front walk from the driveway to the porch, a side path to the backyard gate, or a winding garden path through flower beds, borders make the difference between "there's a walkway here" and "this was planned."`,
      `We pour borders along both sides of the walkway in a single visit, matching the curves and angles of whatever path you've laid out. Straight runs along a concrete sidewalk get crisp, parallel borders. Curved flagstone paths get flowing edges that follow every bend. The concrete is extruded on-site, so there are no seams to break and no sections to shift — just one continuous line on each side.`,
      `For homeowners with sprinkler systems, walkway borders require a bit of planning. We'll walk the path with you during the evening estimate and identify any sprinkler heads or lines that run close to the border route. In most cases, we can route around heads without any rerouting. If a head falls right on the border line, a quick adjustment before pour day keeps everything working. We've done hundreds of walkway jobs alongside irrigation systems — it's a routine part of the planning process.`,
      `Walkway borders pair naturally with matching driveway borders and flower bed edging. When the same color and style runs from the driveway to the front door to the garden beds, your entire yard reads as one coordinated design. That consistency is what separates a house with "some curbing" from a home with a finished landscape. Most walkway border jobs run 50–100 linear feet and take about two hours to pour.`,
    ],
    faqs: [
      {
        question: 'What\'s the minimum walkway width you can border?',
        answer: 'We recommend a minimum finished walkway width of 36 inches between the inside edges of the borders — that\'s wide enough for comfortable single-file walking and meets standard accessibility guidelines. For main entries, 48 inches or wider gives a more generous feel. We measure during the on-site walkthrough.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Can you match walkway borders to my driveway borders?',
        answer: 'Yes, and we recommend it. Matching color, stamp pattern, and profile across all your curbing creates a cohesive look. If your driveway borders are already installed (even by another company), bring us a photo or sample and we\'ll match as closely as possible from our 14 color options.',
      },
      {
        question: 'What about installation near sprinkler lines?',
        answer: 'We deal with sprinkler systems on almost every job. During the walkthrough, we\'ll mark sprinkler heads near the walkway route. Borders are surface-installed with a shallow 3–4 inch base, so they rarely conflict with buried lines. If a head sits right on the path, we can adjust the border route or you can have the head moved before pour day.',
      },
    ],
  },

  'stamped-concrete-curbing': {
    metaDescription: 'Stamped concrete curbing in Utah — 10 patterns including stone, brick, and wood grain. Premium look without the premium cost. Buzz Co Curbing.',
    paragraphs: [
      `Stamped concrete curbing gives you the look of natural stone, brick, or wood grain at a fraction of the material cost. Instead of sourcing, cutting, and mortaring individual pieces, we pour a continuous concrete border and press a pattern into the surface while it's still fresh. The result is a seamless edge that mimics premium materials without the joints, gaps, or settling that come with pieced-together borders.`,
      `We carry 10 stamp patterns, each designed to replicate a specific material. Flagstone and tumbled stone are the most popular — they give a natural, aged look that complements Utah landscapes where real rock is everywhere. Running brick and herringbone patterns work well for traditional homes and formal garden layouts. Our wood-grain stamps are a sleeper hit — they add a rustic, cabin-style texture that looks especially sharp in mountain communities around Logan and Cache Valley.`,
      `The stamping process happens during installation, not after. As the concrete is extruded, we press the pattern roller into the surface before it sets, which means the texture is integral to the border — not a surface coating that wears off. Combined with integral color (our 14 options are mixed into the concrete itself), the stamp and color go all the way through. A chip or scuff doesn't reveal a different color underneath.`,
      `One question we get often: can you combine patterns? In most cases, no — a single border run uses one stamp. But you can absolutely use different patterns on different borders. Flagstone on the flower beds, smooth on the walkway, brick on the driveway — mixing patterns by zone is a great way to add variety without making the yard feel busy. We'll talk through combinations during the evening estimate and help you pick what works best for your home.`,
    ],
    faqs: [
      {
        question: 'Which stamp patterns are most popular?',
        answer: 'Flagstone and tumbled stone account for about 60% of our stamped jobs. They look natural, blend with Utah\'s rocky landscape, and age well. Running brick is the third most popular, especially for homes with brick exteriors. Wood grain is gaining ground fast, particularly in cabin-style and mountain-adjacent neighborhoods.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Does stamping affect the curbing\'s durability?',
        answer: 'Not at all. The stamping is done while the concrete is still plastic, so the pattern is part of the border — not carved or ground into a cured surface. Stamped curbing has the same structural strength as smooth curbing. The only difference is texture, and that texture is sealed to protect it from UV and weather.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Can you combine different stamp patterns on one project?',
        answer: 'Each continuous border run uses one pattern, but you can absolutely use different patterns on different borders within the same yard. For example, flagstone on the garden beds and a smooth profile along the driveway. We bring pattern samples to the walkthrough so you can see them against your actual landscaping before deciding.',
      },
    ],
  },

  'custom-color-curbing': {
    metaDescription: 'Custom color concrete curbing in Utah — 14 integral colors matched to your home. Color runs all the way through. Buzz Co Curbing.',
    paragraphs: [
      `Color is what makes concrete curbing disappear into your landscape — or stand out as a deliberate accent. We offer 14 integral concrete colors, meaning the pigment is mixed directly into the concrete before it's poured. This isn't paint. This isn't stain. The color goes all the way through the border, so a chip or scrape doesn't expose a gray core underneath.`,
      `The difference between integral color and surface-applied color is durability. Painted curbing starts peeling within a year or two. Surface stains fade unevenly and need reapplication. Integral color is permanent — it's literally part of the concrete. Over time it may lighten slightly from UV exposure, but re-sealing every 2–3 years restores the richness and keeps it looking like the day it was poured.`,
      `Our color range covers warm earth tones (buff, sandstone, desert tan), cool grays (pewter, charcoal, slate), and deeper options (terra cotta, chocolate brown, dark walnut). We also carry a natural concrete gray for homeowners who want the clean look without added color. The most popular picks in Utah are buff and sandstone — they complement the tan and brown tones in local landscape rock and blend naturally with stucco and stone home exteriors.`,
      `Color matching is part of our walkthrough process. We bring the full set of color sample chips so you can hold them against your home's siding, trim, foundation, or landscape rock under natural light. Seeing the samples in your actual yard — not under fluorescent showroom lighting — is the only reliable way to pick. If your neighbor's curbing caught your eye, tell us and we'll identify the color so yours matches or complements it.`,
    ],
    faqs: [
      {
        question: 'Does integral color fade over time?',
        answer: 'Integral color is UV-stable, but like any outdoor surface it can lighten slightly over years of sun exposure. Sealing the curbing protects against this and keeps the color rich. We seal every job at installation and recommend re-sealing every 2–3 years. With regular sealing, the color holds strong for decades.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Can I see color samples before ordering?',
        answer: 'Yes — it\'s part of our standard process. During the walkthrough, we bring the full set of 14 color sample chips. You hold them against your home, landscape rock, and existing hardscape in natural light so there are no surprises. We never ask you to pick a color from a website photo.',
      },
      {
        question: 'How does color matching work if I want to match my home exterior?',
        answer: 'We match by eye using our 14-color sample set against your home\'s actual exterior under natural light. We\'ll hold chips against your siding, brick, stone, or stucco and narrow it down to the closest option. It won\'t be a laboratory-exact match, but integral concrete colors are designed to complement common building materials — most homeowners find a near-perfect fit.',
      },
    ],
  },

  'mower-style-curbing': {
    metaDescription: 'Mower-style curbing in Utah — low profile so your mower rides the edge. No more hand trimming. Same-week scheduling from Buzz Co Curbing.',
    paragraphs: [
      `If you mow your own lawn, mower-style curbing will change your Saturday mornings. It's a low-profile curb design — about 3 inches tall and 5–6 inches wide — shaped so your mower wheel rides right along the top edge. That means the blade cuts cleanly up to the border with zero hand trimming, zero edging, and zero kneeling down with a string trimmer to clean up what the mower missed.`,
      `This is our most practical curb style, and it's the top choice among homeowners who maintain their own yards. The profile sits just barely above the lawn surface, creating a clean separation between grass and bed without a tall wall that catches mower decks or creates a shadow line. It looks like a subtle, built-in feature of the landscape — not an add-on.`,
      `Mower-style curbing works anywhere you have lawn meeting a planting bed, rock area, or tree ring. It's especially popular along long, straight bed lines where hand trimming would eat up 20 minutes every mow. But it handles curves just as well — our extrusion machine follows whatever shape you need, so you get the trimming benefit on curved beds too, not just the easy straight runs.`,
      `Durability under mower weight is a common question, and it's a good one. Our mower-style profile is poured at the same concrete thickness as our taller curb styles — about 3 inches wide at the base. Concrete handles weight. A standard residential riding mower weighs around 500 pounds, and a 21-inch push mower is under 80. Neither comes close to stressing a concrete border. We've installed thousands of linear feet of mower-style curbing across Utah, and wheel traffic has never been a failure point.`,
    ],
    faqs: [
      {
        question: 'Can my mower wheel actually ride on the curbing?',
        answer: 'Yes — that\'s exactly what it\'s designed for. The flat, wide top surface gives your mower wheel a stable riding edge. You run one wheel along the curbing and the blade cuts right up to the border line. Works with push mowers, self-propelled mowers, and riding mowers. No trimming required afterward.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Is mower-style curbing lower than other curb styles?',
        answer: 'Yes. Our mower-style profile sits about 2–3 inches above grade with a flat top, compared to our standard decorative profiles that range from 4–6 inches tall. The lower height is the whole point — it stays below your mower deck so the blade can cut right up to the edge without catching or scalping.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Can mower-style curbing handle the weight of a riding mower?',
        answer: 'Easily. A typical residential riding mower weighs 400–600 pounds distributed across four wheels. Our curbing is solid concrete poured at a consistent 3-inch thickness. It\'s designed for exactly this kind of load. We\'ve never had a curbing failure from mower traffic — the concrete is more than strong enough.',
      },
    ],
  },

  'commercial-curbing': {
    metaDescription: 'Commercial concrete curbing in Utah — HOAs, apartments, retail, municipal projects. Volume pricing, professional results. Buzz Co Curbing.',
    paragraphs: [
      `Commercial properties need curbing that scales — hundreds or thousands of linear feet across parking lot islands, building perimeters, common areas, and entry features. Buzz Co handles commercial concrete curbing for HOAs, apartment complexes, retail centers, office parks, and municipal projects throughout Utah. Same quality as our residential work, but built for the scope and timelines that commercial projects demand.`,
      `The difference between residential and commercial curbing isn't the product — it's the logistics. Commercial jobs require coordination with property managers, tenants, landscaping crews, and sometimes city permitting. We handle the scheduling so installation happens in phases that minimize disruption to tenants and customers. A 2,000-foot apartment complex job doesn't shut down the whole property — we section it off and move through systematically.`,
      `For HOAs and property management companies, consistency matters. When you're curbing 40 townhome units or a multi-building complex, every border needs to match — same color, same profile, same quality from the first unit to the last. Our integral color system and machine extrusion process ensure uniformity across the entire project. No batch color variation, no handwork inconsistencies, no unit that looks different from its neighbor.`,
      `Volume pricing applies to commercial projects over 500 linear feet. The per-foot rate drops as footage increases because our setup and mobilization costs are spread across more production. We provide detailed written proposals with per-foot pricing, project phasing schedules, and completion timelines. For large projects, we can also provide references from other commercial properties we've completed in the area. Call for a commercial estimate — we'll walk the property and scope it with your maintenance team.`,
    ],
    faqs: [
      {
        question: 'What\'s the minimum footage for commercial pricing?',
        answer: 'Our commercial pricing tier starts at 500 linear feet. Below that, residential per-foot rates apply. Most commercial projects we handle fall between 1,000 and 5,000 linear feet. For very large projects (10,000+ feet), we provide custom proposals with phased pricing and scheduling.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Can you match existing curbing on the property?',
        answer: 'In most cases, yes. If the existing curbing was done in a standard integral color, we can match it closely from our 14-color lineup. We\'ll pull a sample or photo of the existing work and compare on-site. For older curbing that\'s faded significantly, we may recommend re-sealing the existing sections after the new work is installed so everything looks uniform.',
      },
      {
        question: 'What\'s the typical timeline for a large commercial project?',
        answer: 'It depends on total footage and phasing requirements. A 1,000-foot apartment complex with no phasing restrictions takes 2–3 days of pour time. A 5,000-foot HOA project phased across multiple weeks to minimize resident disruption might take 3–4 weeks total. We provide a detailed timeline in every commercial proposal so your management team can plan around it.',
      },
    ],
  },

  'curbing-repair': {
    metaDescription: 'Concrete curbing repair in Utah — fix cracks, chips, and damage. Color and pattern matching. Localized repair by Buzz Co Curbing.',
    paragraphs: [
      `Concrete curbing is durable, but it's not indestructible. Tree roots heave it. Snowplows clip the corners. Settling ground opens cracks. Heavy equipment rolls over it during a remodel. Whatever caused the damage, you've got a section of curbing that looks broken while the rest of the yard looks great. That's where curbing repair comes in — fix the damaged section without replacing the entire run.`,
      `We specialize in localized repair, meaning we remove and repour only the damaged section. If you have 200 feet of curbing and 15 feet is cracked, you don't need 200 feet of new concrete. We cut out the damaged portion, prep the base, and pour a new section that ties into the existing borders on both ends. It's faster, cheaper, and avoids tearing up landscaping that's perfectly fine.`,
      `The trickiest part of curbing repair is color and pattern matching. If your curbing is three years old and has faded slightly, new concrete in the "same" color will look different. We address this two ways: first, we select the closest integral color from our 14 options using sample chips matched against your existing curbing in natural light. Second, we recommend re-sealing both the repaired section and the adjacent existing curbing at the same time — sealant evens out color differences and makes the transition much less noticeable.`,
      `Not all damage needs repair. Hairline surface cracks are cosmetic and can often be addressed with re-sealing alone. Larger cracks, heaved sections, and broken chunks do need repour. During the on-site estimate, Justin will assess the damage honestly and tell you whether repair, re-sealing, or replacement is the right call. We'd rather send you home with a $150 re-seal than sell you a $900 repair you don't need.`,
    ],
    faqs: [
      {
        question: 'Can you match the color of my old curbing?',
        answer: 'We match as closely as possible using our 14 integral color options. Older curbing may have faded from UV exposure, so a fresh pour in the "same" color can look slightly different. Re-sealing both the new and existing sections after the repair helps blend them together. In most cases, the color match is very close and any difference is only noticeable if you\'re looking for it.',
      },
      {
        question: 'What types of damage can be repaired?',
        answer: 'We repair cracked sections, chipped edges, heaved portions (from tree roots or ground settling), and broken-off chunks. If the curbing has shifted but isn\'t cracked, we can sometimes reset it without repouring. Hairline surface cracks are usually cosmetic and can be managed with re-sealing rather than repair. We assess on-site and give you an honest recommendation.',
      },
      {
        question: 'How does repair cost compare to full replacement?',
        answer: 'Repair is almost always cheaper than replacing the entire run. If 10% of your curbing is damaged, repair costs roughly 15–20% of a full replacement — you\'re paying for the damaged section plus tie-in work on each end. Full replacement only makes sense if the majority of the curbing is damaged or if you want to change the color or style entirely.',
      },
    ],
  },

  'curbing-resealing': {
    metaDescription: 'Curbing re-sealing in Utah — restore color vibrancy, protect against UV and water damage. Every 2–3 years. Buzz Co Curbing.',
    paragraphs: [
      `Sealing your concrete curbing is the single best thing you can do to protect your investment. A quality sealant blocks UV rays that fade color, repels water that causes freeze-thaw cracking, and restores the color vibrancy that made your curbing look great on day one. We recommend re-sealing every 2–3 years, and every client who follows that schedule still has curbing that looks nearly new — even after a decade.`,
      `The re-sealing process is straightforward. We clean the curbing surface to remove dirt, moss, and debris, then apply a penetrating acrylic sealant that bonds to the concrete pores. The sealant dries clear with a subtle sheen that deepens the integral color — think of it like wetting a river stone. That richness lasts 2–3 years before the next application is needed. The whole process takes a few hours for a typical residential property.`,
      `One of the most common calls we get is from homeowners who had curbing installed 5–7 years ago and never sealed it. The color has faded, the surface feels chalky, and they're wondering if it needs to be replaced. In most cases, it doesn't. A thorough cleaning and re-seal brings back 80–90% of the original color depth. It's a fraction of the cost of replacement and extends the curbing's life significantly.`,
      `We re-seal curbing we installed, and we also re-seal curbing installed by other companies. The concrete is the same material regardless of who poured it. If your curbing is structurally sound but looking tired, re-sealing is the answer. If there are cracks or damage, we'll flag that during the visit and recommend repair before sealing — sealant protects good concrete, but it doesn't fix broken concrete.`,
    ],
    faqs: [
      {
        question: 'How often should I reseal my curbing?',
        answer: 'Every 2–3 years is the sweet spot for Utah\'s climate. Our summers are intense (UV fading) and our winters bring freeze-thaw cycles that stress unsealed concrete. If your curbing is in direct sun all day, lean toward every 2 years. Shaded areas can stretch to 3. We\'ll recommend a schedule based on your specific exposure during the service visit.',
      },
      {
        question: 'Can you reseal curbing installed by another company?',
        answer: 'Yes. Concrete is concrete — the sealant doesn\'t care who poured it. We clean the surface, assess the condition, and apply the same sealant we use on our own installations. If we spot any damage that needs repair before sealing, we\'ll let you know. We reseal third-party curbing regularly and it\'s a straightforward service.',
      },
      {
        question: 'How long does the sealant last?',
        answer: 'Our acrylic penetrating sealant lasts 2–3 years under normal Utah conditions. High-traffic areas or full-sun exposure may wear faster. You\'ll know it\'s time to reseal when the surface starts looking chalky or the color seems washed out compared to areas that stay shaded. It\'s a gradual fade, not a sudden failure, so you have time to schedule the next application.',
      },
    ],
  },
};

const content = contentMap[service.slug] || {
  metaDescription: `${service.name} in Utah by Buzz Co Curbing. Same-week scheduling available. Get a free estimate today.`,
  paragraphs: [service.description],
  faqs: [],
};

const pageTitle = `${service.name} in Utah | Buzz Co Curbing`;

const faqSchema = content.faqs.length > 0
  ? {
      '@context': 'https://schema.org',
      '@type': 'FAQPage',
      mainEntity: content.faqs.map(faq => ({
        '@type': 'Question',
        name: faq.question,
        acceptedAnswer: {
          '@type': 'Answer',
          text: faq.answer,
        },
      })),
    }
  : null;

const breadcrumbSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
  itemListElement: [
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://www.buzzcocurb.com/' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Services', item: 'https://www.buzzcocurb.com/services/' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 3, name: service.name },
  ],
};

const serviceSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Service',
  name: service.name,
  description: service.description,
  provider: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Buzz Co Curbing',
    url: 'https://www.buzzcocurb.com/',
  },
  areaServed: {
    '@type': 'State',
    name: 'Utah',
  },
};

const schemas = [breadcrumbSchema, serviceSchema, ...(faqSchema ? [faqSchema] : [])];
---

<BaseLayout
  title={pageTitle}
  description={content.metaDescription}
  schema={schemas}
  geoPlacename="Logan"
  canonical={`https://www.buzzcocurb.com/services/${service.slug}/`}
>
  <!-- Breadcrumb -->
  <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="pt-28 pb-0 bg-warm-white">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-8">
      <ol class="flex items-center gap-2 font-data text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-warm-muted">
        <li><a href="/" class="hover:text-dark transition-colors">Home</a></li>
        <li aria-hidden="true">/</li>
        <li><a href="/services/" class="hover:text-dark transition-colors">Services</a></li>
        <li aria-hidden="true">/</li>
        <li class="text-dark/70">{service.name}</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- Hero / Heading -->
  <section class="pt-10 pb-16 md:pt-14 md:pb-24 bg-warm-white">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-8">
      <p class="section-label mb-4">SERVICES</p>
      <h1 class="font-heading text-section-heading font-bold text-dark mb-6">{service.name} in Utah</h1>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-dark/60 max-w-2xl leading-relaxed">{service.description}</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Body Copy -->
  <section class="pb-16 md:pb-24 bg-warm-white">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-8">
      {content.paragraphs.map(p => (
        <p class="font-body text-base md:text-lg text-dark/70 leading-relaxed mb-6">{p}</p>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  {content.faqs.length > 0 && (
    <section class="pb-16 md:pb-24 bg-warm-white" aria-label="Frequently asked questions">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-8">
        <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-dark mb-10">Common Questions</h2>
        <div class="divide-y divide-dark/10">
          {content.faqs.map((faq, i) => (
            <div class="faq-item py-6" data-faq>
              <button
                type="button"
                class="faq-toggle flex w-full items-center justify-between gap-4 text-left"
                aria-expanded="false"
                aria-controls={`faq-answer-${service.slug}-${i}`}
              >
                <span class="font-heading font-semibold text-lg text-dark pr-4">{faq.question}</span>
                <span class="faq-icon shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center w-8 h-8 rounded-none border border-dark/10 text-accent font-heading text-xl leading-none transition-transform duration-300" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
              </button>
              <div
                id={`faq-answer-${service.slug}-${i}`}
                class="faq-answer overflow-hidden"
              >
                <p class="font-body text-dark/70 leading-relaxed pt-4 pb-2">{faq.answer}</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  )}

  <!-- Related Services -->
  <section class="pb-16 md:pb-24 bg-warm-white" aria-label="Related services">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-8">
      <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-dark mb-8">Related Services</h2>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
        {related.map(rel => (
          <a href={`/services/${rel.slug}/`} class="group bg-warm-gray border border-dark/[0.06] rounded-card p-8 transition-all duration-300 hover:shadow-lg hover:shadow-dark/[0.06] hover:-translate-y-1">
            <p class="font-data text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-accent mb-3">{rel.shortName}</p>
            <h3 class="font-heading font-semibold text-lg text-dark mb-3 group-hover:text-accent transition-colors">{rel.name}</h3>
            <p class="font-body text-sm text-dark/60 leading-relaxed">{rel.description}</p>
            <p class="font-heading font-medium text-sm text-accent mt-4 flex items-center gap-1">
              Learn more <span class="transition-transform duration-300 group-hover:translate-x-1">→</span>
            </p>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="pb-20 md:pb-32 bg-warm-white">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-8 text-center">
      <div class="rounded-card bg-warm-gray border border-dark/[0.06] p-10 md:p-16">
        <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-dark mb-4">Ready to get this done?</h2>
        <p class="font-body text-dark/60 mb-8 max-w-xl mx-auto">Justin comes out in the evening so both homeowners can be there. You walk the yard together, pick colors and patterns, and get a firm price on the spot. If it works, the crew is there the next morning.</p>
        <a href="/logan/get-estimate/" class="btn-primary">
          <span class="btn-bg" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <span class="btn-text">Get a Free Estimate</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
